{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505598","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505598"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:33:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:33:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2458"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2458","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2458"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.55,0.03,0.39,0.02,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2458"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100215"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2458","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2458"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2458"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82613"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"297"},{"type":"tags","id":"4100"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2014"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2028"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9238"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9421"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11629"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14308"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33204"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43160"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100215","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/100215"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 54-year-old G2P2 woman presents to the GP clinic for her annual health check-up. She is asymptomatic and appears well. She is married and still practices vaginal sex with her husband without regular condom use. She has a history of bacterial vaginosis infection three years ago, which was treated. She drinks alcohol once or twice monthly and has smoked 15 cigarettes daily for the past 15 years. Her last cervical screening test was done a year ago and showed HPV (not 16/18) and possible low-grade squamous intraepithelial lesion (pLSIL). She was subsequently asked to repeat the HPV screening 12 months later which was subsequently performed at this visit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe results of her 12 month follow up HPV screening returns the following results: \u003Cbr /\u003EOncogenic HPV and genotype: \u003Cbr /\u003EHPV 16/18: not detected \u003Cbr /\u003EHPV (not 16/18): detected\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EReflex LBC: pLSIL\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the recommended next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Refer to a specialist for colposcopy","Using the current sample, run LBC","Repeat HPV testing in 12 months","Retest for LBC only in 6 weeks","Repeat HPV screening in 6 weeks"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s results detected HPV (not 16/18) and a possible LSIL in the LBC in her first visit, and a confirmatory HPV screening 12 months after showed persistent HPV (not 16/18) infection. Importantly, this patient is over 50 and falls into the higher risk subgroup, regardless of LBC. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn such cases, as this is the second result with HPV (not 16/18) the recommended management is to\u003Cstrong\u003E refer the patient to a specialist for a colposcopic assessment\u003C/strong\u003E. The colposcopy allows for collection of the LBC sample if not already know as well as visualisation of the cervix under magnification, identification of the level of dysplasia, and performance of a biopsy if necessary to classify the potential cervical intraepithelial neoplasia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGroups considered high risk, requiring referral to a specialist for a colposcopic assessment after two positive results with HPV (not 16/18) include participants who are:\u003Cbr /\u003E\u2022 Aged 50+ years \u003Cbr /\u003E\u2022 Aboriginal and/or Torres Strait Islander \u003Cbr /\u003E\u2022 Overdue for screening by at least 2 years at initial screen\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERequesting an LBC \u003C/strong\u003Eis the correct option if the patient is \u0026lt;50 years old, not an Aboriginal and/or Torres Strait Islander, or if the patient is not overdue for her routine HPV screening. However, since this scenario features a woman who is \u0026gt;50 years old, she should be directly referred to colposcopy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther options such as \u003Cstrong\u003Ecollecting new samples for LBC in 6 weeks\u003C/strong\u003E are not indicated in this case, as this should only be repeated if the sample is considered inadequate. \u003Cstrong\u003EReturning to routine cervical screening in 5 years\u003C/strong\u003E is also not appropriate, given the presence of HPV (not 16/18) and the possible LSIL.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Patients who are \u003E50 years old, identify as an Aboriginal and/or Torres Strait Islander, or missed their routine screening should be referred to colposcopy after detecting HPV (not 16/18) twice"],"references":["Peirson L, Fitzpatrick-Lewis D, Ciliska D, Warren R. Screening for cervical cancer: a systematic review and meta-analysis. Syst Rev 2013; 2:35.","Management of oncogenic HPV test results - Introduction [Internet]. www.cancer.org.au. Available from: https://www.cancer.org.au/clinical-guidelines/cervical-cancer/cervical-cancer-screening/management-of-oncogenic-hpv-test-results","Australian Centre for the Prevention of Cervical Cancer. Cervical screening pathway quick reference guide. Melbourne (AU): ACPCC; 2024 Available at: https://acpcc.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/NCSP-quick-ref-guide-WEB-DEC2024.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82613"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2458"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82613","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/82613"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-24T21:18:10+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-24T21:18:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2458"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100215"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt"